## 5. Silence Systems

Silence is the most important sound in the project.

### 5.1 Intentional silence
- TIER 01 (silence) scenes per `narrative-density-system.mdc`: **all audio ducks to -inf** during the scene's scroll envelope, with a 1.4s fade.
- The audience experiences the **room being removed** — the most cinematic sound effect available.
- Silence holds for the **full** scene duration. No "subtle" continuation.

### 5.2 Emotional absence
- After a TIER 05 → TIER 01 transition: silence is **delayed** to begin **300ms after** the visual transition completes, then fades in over 800ms. The audience hears the climax, then hears it removed.
- This is the audio equivalent of the **freeze frame** in `human-irregularity-system.mdc`.

### 5.3 Audio withdrawal
- During chapter transitions (T2 per `transition-system.mdc`): outgoing chapter ambience ducks to **40%** during the seam, incoming chapter ambience fades in **after** the visual settle, never simultaneous.
- Result: the audio "lags" the image by ~200ms — the same lag that gives film cuts their weight.

### 5.4 Pacing through silence
- Maximum continuous ambience runtime: **90 seconds**. After that, a **silence pocket** of ≥ 4 seconds must occur (often aligned with a TIER 01 scene).
- Silence pockets prevent the audience from **stopping hearing** the ambience (auditory adaptation kicks in around 90s; we reset before then).

### 5.5 Contrast through silence
- The page's most powerful audio moment is the **first silence** after the hero ambience starts. It tells the audience that audio in this project is **deliberate**, not background.

---

## 6. Interaction Audio Rules

The project rejects the entire genre of "interactive web audio".

### 6.1 Forbidden interaction sounds
- ❌ Click sounds on links / buttons.
- ❌ Hover sounds (any kind).
- ❌ Scroll-driven audio events (every scroll tick triggering a sample).
- ❌ Form input feedback sounds.
- ❌ Modal open/close sounds (modals are forbidden anyway, per `cinematic-language.mdc`).
- ❌ Page load chimes, "ready" sounds, splash audio.
- ❌ Cursor-state-change sounds.

### 6.2 Allowed interaction sounds
- ✅ **Single tactile micro-tone** on opening the chapter index (≤ -28 dB, 1.2s decay, low-mid frequency).
- ✅ **Single tactile micro-tone** on case study slide advance (only if chapter declares `tactileMicroTones.enabled: true`).
- ✅ **Subtle environmental response** — when WebGL atmosphere reacts to scroll velocity, the ambience may subtly modulate its low-frequency content (±2 dB at 80 Hz). This is the **only** scroll-reactive audio behavior.
- ✅ **Toggle confirmation tone** (≤ -32 dB, 0.4s decay) when the user enables / disables sound for the first time.

### 6.3 Tactile micro-tone spec
- Always low-mid frequency content (160 Hz – 800 Hz).
- Always single, short, decaying.
- Never percussive ("click" / "tick").
- Designed to feel like the **air responding**, not the **interface clicking**.
- Reference: a finger gently tapping a wooden tabletop in an empty room, recorded at distance.

---

## 7. Spatial Audio Logic

The project does **not** use HRTF / 3D positional audio (overkill, perf cost). It uses **2D spatial cueing** via stereo placement and frequency content.

### 7.1 Directional atmosphere
- Hero ambience: panned slightly **left** (mid-side, 20% bias) to suggest the world extending beyond the frame.
- Cultural chapters: ambience panned **right** in alternating chapters (cinematic spatial alternation).
- Human chapters: **dead center** (intimacy = no width).
- Closing: width **collapses** to mono over the chapter duration.

### 7.2 Environmental depth
- Ambience EQ: **gently rolled off above 8 kHz** to suggest distance / room boundaries.
- Transition resonance: **rolled off above 4 kHz** to read as sub-audible weight, not a "swoosh".
- Tactile micro-tones: **full bandwidth** (the only audio that "speaks" near the audience).

### 7.3 Cinematic positioning
- The audience is always in the **same listening position** across chapters — the same seat in the same theatre. We change the **scene around them**, not their position.
- No audio "moves" through the stereo field. Things may **fade in / out**, but never **traverse**.

### 7.4 Emotional distance
- Loudness signals proximity. Quiet ambience = **far**. Slightly louder ambience = **closer**.
- The hero ambience is the **furthest** ambience on the page. The closing ambience is **closer** (the audience has been brought into the room).
- This is opposite of typical web audio (which gets quieter at the end). It is **deliberate** — the project closes by **drawing the audience in**, not pushing them out.

### 7.5 Low-frequency grounding
- Each chapter's ambience contains **low-frequency content** (60–120 Hz) at -28 to -32 dB. This grounds the chapter in the listener's body without being audible as "bass".
- Removed entirely on mobile (small speakers cannot reproduce; would only add noise).

---

## 8. Audio Performance Rules

### 8.1 Lazy loading
- Audio assets are **never** loaded at first paint.
- Hero ambience loads after the hero intro completes (audio activation happens after the user explicitly enables sound).
- Subsequent chapter ambience loads on chapter approach (`IntersectionObserver` rootMargin: 100%).
- Transition resonance: pre-loaded for the **next** chapter only, never for the entire page.

### 8.2 Muted-by-default behavior
- Audio is **off** on first visit. Always.
- A small editorial toggle (`sound · off / on`) sits in the header, labeled in body type (not an icon). On click, the user enables audio.
- State persists in `localStorage` under key `strategicland.audio = "on" | "off"`.
- On enable, the project plays a single confirmation tone (Section 6.2) — this is the **only** audio that plays without scroll context.

### 8.3 Optional activation
- The activation is a **one-time courtesy** — once enabled, audio remains enabled across visits.
- The toggle is **never animated to draw attention**. It is an editorial element, not a CTA.
- No "tap to enable sound" overlays. No "click for the full experience" prompts. Both are forbidden.

### 8.4 Reduced mobile usage
- On `< md` breakpoint:
  - Transition resonance: **disabled** (sub-bass content unreproducible on phone speakers).
  - Tactile micro-tones: **disabled**.
  - Ambience: optional, lower bitrate (64 kbps AAC), shorter loops (30s).
  - Total audio budget halved (≤ 200 KB initial, ≤ 100 KB per chapter).
- On data-saver mode (`navigator.connection.saveData === true`): **all audio disabled**, toggle hidden.

### 8.5 Adaptive quality
- Use `Audio` element with `preload="metadata"` (never `auto`) to defer download.
- For Web Audio API integration (ducking, fades, low-pass filter for ambience, sub modulation), instantiate `AudioContext` only on user gesture (browser autoplay policy).
- A single `AudioContext` per session. Disposed on route change between non-audio routes.

### 8.6 Power-save respect
- If the page is hidden (`document.visibilityState === "hidden"`), audio pauses in 2 seconds. Resumes on return.
- If the user has not interacted in **120 seconds** (no scroll, no pointer), ambience ducks to 40% (assumes inattentive listening).
- Battery API (where supported): if `< 20%` battery, ambience disabled with a one-line subtle disclosure in the header tooltip.

---

## 9. Audio + Reduced Motion

`prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` is a signal about **all** sensory motion, not just visual:

- All ambience volume capped at -32 dB (50% of standard).
- Transition resonance disabled (the sub wash can be vestibularly disruptive).
- Tactile micro-tones disabled.
- Silence pockets remain (silence is restful, not motion).

---

## 10. Implementation Standards

### File structure
- `lib/sound/AudioDirector.ts` — singleton, owns the AudioContext and routing.
- `lib/sound/ambienceLayer.ts` — chapter ambience playback + crossfade.
- `lib/sound/transitionResonance.ts` — fires sub wash on chapter transitions.
- `lib/sound/tactileTone.ts` — micro-tone playback for declared interactions.
- `lib/sound/silenceController.ts` — orchestrates ducking during TIER 01 scenes.
- `lib/sound/types.ts` — `ChapterAudio`, `AudioState`.
- `components/sound/SoundToggle.tsx` — header editorial toggle.
- `public/audio/` — all `.m4a` and `.opus` files.

### Hooks
- `useAudioEnabled()` — boolean from `localStorage` + AudioContext state.
- `useChapterAudio(audioConfig)` — registers a chapter's audio profile with the director.
- `useTactileTone(target)` — wires a tactile tone to an interaction.
- `useDuckOnTier(tier)` — used inside `<SceneShell>` to duck during TIER 01.

### Integration with existing systems
- `<TransitionDirector>` (per `transition-system.mdc`) calls into `AudioDirector` on `play("chapter:cross")` to fire transition resonance.
- `<SceneShell>` (per `narrative-density-system.mdc`) calls `useDuckOnTier(tier)` to coordinate ducking.
- `useScrollVelocity()` (per `scroll-system.mdc`) is consumed by `AudioDirector` to modulate ambient low-frequency content (±2 dB at 80 Hz, damped over 800ms).

### Variance integration
- Per `human-irregularity-system.mdc`: ambience loops have **±150ms jittered start offsets** so two playthroughs do not align identically. The loop point itself is fixed; the **entry point** drifts.
- Transition resonance peak amplitude jittered ±0.6 dB.
- Tactile tone pitch jittered ±5 cents (imperceptible but prevents identical-replay machine feel).

### Accessibility
- Audio must **never** carry critical information. Visual is always primary; audio is supplemental atmosphere.
- The audio toggle is keyboard-focusable, ARIA-labeled `Toggle ambient sound`, with state announced via `aria-live`.
- All audio respects `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- Provide a transcript / description in the colophon page for any chapter that uses field recordings of cultural significance (provenance + acknowledgment).

---

## 11. DO / DON'T

### DO
- DO ship the project muted by default.
- DO use field-recorded ambience only.
- DO duck audio during TIER 01 silence scenes.
- DO crossfade chapter ambience with the audio lagging the visual by ~200ms.
- DO declare per-chapter audio profiles colocated with atmosphere config.
- DO disable transition resonance on mobile.
- DO end the page in silence (closing chapter fades to dead air).

### DON'T
- DON'T add music — orchestral, ambient melodic, drone, or otherwise.
- DON'T add UI sounds (clicks, hovers, swooshes, chimes).
- DON'T autoplay audio. Ever.
- DON'T use cinematic stings (risers, impacts, "boom" transitions).
- DON'T move sounds through the stereo field (no traversal).
- DON'T overlay multiple ambiences simultaneously (one per chapter).
- DON'T let ambience run continuously > 90 seconds without a silence pocket.
- DON'T prompt the user with "click to enable the full experience".
- DON'T treat audio as load-bearing — the experience must hold without it.

---

## 12. Cinematic Rationale

- **Music tells the audience what to feel**. We refuse this. The audience must arrive at their feeling **on their own** — that is the difference between cinema and advertising.
- **Field recordings** are the difference between **a place** and **a soundtrack**. A wind recording from a real Patagonian valley carries meaning a synth pad never can, even if both are technically "ambient".
- **Audio lagging visual by 200ms** at chapter transitions reproduces the temporal staggering of live experience. In real life, light reaches us instantly; sound reaches us with delay. Acknowledging this in the project makes the audience's nervous system **trust the space**.
- **Silence as the most powerful audio event** is a principle from John Cage and from the entire history of cinema sound design (Walter Murch's "rule of two and a half" for sound dimensions). The project respects this lineage.
- **Muted-by-default** is not a UX concession. It is an **editorial stance** — we are not auto-playing a film at the audience. We are inviting them in.
- **Sound is not load-bearing** is the safety net for the entire system: if a user disables audio, they get a coherent experience. If audio were load-bearing, we would be back in the territory of trailer-style "wow moments" — the genre we are explicitly building **against**.
